When you draw persons(humans,aliens,etc.) think organic.<br>
When you draw mecha however, think technical...<br>
Like how PK said in the tut you have to think about the purpose of the machine before you start doing it but I'll tell you what I'd do if drawing a general purpose machine. <br>
First thing I'd want to get away from the whole humanoid thing. It's tiresome and boring though probably easiest to do since it takes the least imagination. <br>
Next up I'll draw the skeleton of the machine during my sketches.I mean do out the entire frame(no weapons, no equipment,no nothing) Remember to include certain specifics(if it is to be manned then it needs a cockpit. The usual cockpit area is in the chest and accessed from either the front or back) Let's be a bit different and have the cockpit in either the head or in the waist. Better the head...because the waist is not likely since it houses all sorts of motors for the movement  of the legs.<br>
Think about ball joints and such and think about functionality. Instead of putting a mess of &quot;detail&quot; lines in the torso area think about how agile this suit is to be. If supposed to be for fighting it should be very agile so should be able to twist at the waist and bend over and such. Therefore the middle torso should be segmented so that each segment can fold over the other and bend downwards or upwards; whichever direction you think of. Sketches are nice for this.<br>
The arms don't need anything like this unless you're being imaginative(yayyy!!) and want something that can be a bit more useful than a humanoid hand. Remember to try to stray away from that for now. Helps the creative process.<br>
Go about this way of thinking for the entire frame top to bottom and you'll be done after a while once you keep on thinking about what someone would have to do to build it. If you don't think you can build it  or at least use it as a basis for construction then you're trying hard enough. Remember it's a robot not a giant man in a suit.<br>
Now to details...<br>
Fingers...many artists get lazy and don't do this but think a little. How will robots fingers move in a manned suit? The controls from the cockpit must be sending signals to move the fingers but not directly. It sends it to the motors which turn to lift the finger. Therefore these motors must be included. Look at your own hand and think about how it moves and how a machine can emulate it. A few segments in the hand will be necessary especially to execute the folding action of a hand to grab something. The best neck design would also be segmented giving a full 360-degree range of motion.<br>
If you have weapons you have more to think about as well.<br>
For instance if you want a built-in shoulder cannon then the shoulder must be bulky to house the cannon and the link to the generator within the suit. This is because space would also be needed for the shoulder motors used to lift the arms and such.<br>
(For motors on the robot just think about how your muscles work to help you move. Exposing a few of these motors adds to coolness but doesn't make much sense if it's for fighting because then they'd be easy targets)<br>
Without weapons however it's just a case of filling out the suit with the exterior covers which would be to your own approval but having the underneath frame will affect how you draw the exterior because it'll be forcing you to think of functionality.<br>
Hope that helped you out somewhat. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showLocalUserPublicProfile?login=monkeydispenser>monkey dispenser</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Karbonite</span><br> <font color=#336699>(8/11/02 4:23:57 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=4173.topic&index=4>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.monkeydispenser.com/images/winkerlogo.jpg height=130 width=115></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: most of you will yell at me...</span><hr size=1> Hmmmm...I still stand by the fact that the principles for drawing mecha are similar to those for drawing people.<br>
